9.msg:
A mark is an exact location in the 
text you can teleport yourself to,
or use as a command parameter.

It's invisible in VIM, but here in
Textland it's marked with a flag.
The name of the mark is the
letter written on the flag.

10.msg:
Local marks are marks that are
private to the text you're currently on.
Lower case 'a' - 'z', for example, are
local marks. Two different texts can
have the mark 'a' on both of them at
the same time while each mark
denotes a different location.

11.msg:
I just know they exist, but

You should type ` followed
by the mark name to be
teleported there, or you can
use it as a motion after an 
operator such as d, y, c etc.

13.msg:
A global mark denotes a location in
a text along with the specific buffer
(file). The global mark is unique and
can't be shared between two texts;
A new global mark will replace the
old one with the same name even if
the older one was in a different text
or buffer.
Capitals A-Z are global marks.

14.msg:
There are also local marks, which
are private to the current text. But
you'd better consult with Mr. White
on that Chief!

15.msg:
You should use backtick ( ` )
followed by a global mark name
to teleport yourself to that mark.
Since a global mark might reside
in a different buffer, the current
buffer might change to reflect the
new location.

If a global mark is on the same
text as you, you may also use it
as a motion for operators such
as yank, delete, etc.

8.msg:
You can see a list of all the
marks in the current text, as
well as the global ones by using
the ':marks' command. You can
narrow the list by providing the
flags you're interested in. For
example ':marks Spencer' will
list the marks S, p, e, n, c & r.

Oh, and you can remove marks
with ':delm' command. Just list
the marks or use '!' for all local
ones.

9.msg:
Big Bug is the highest ranking bug
here in Textland, commanding the
bugs invasion. It was told that when
marks are positioned on a special
underground text, he'll be destroyed.
I never saw this text, but you told me
there is another text in the sky just
like it which reveals the marks to use.
